       <item>
        <widget class="QLabel" name="packetDefinitionFilesLabel">
         <property name="maximumSize">
          <size>
           <width>200</width>
           <height>25</height>
          </size>
         </property>
         <property name="font">
          <font>
           <family>Sans Serif Collection</family>
           <pointsize>12</pointsize>
           <underline>true</underline>
          </font>
         </property>
         <property name="toolTip">
          <string>&lt;html&gt;&lt;head/&gt;&lt;body&gt;&lt;p&gt;Telemetry definitions contain all of the information needed to decode a recieved telemetry packet. A header definition contains fields which will always be present when recieving a packet and is good for defining packet headers, or a singular packet type when an interface will only ever receive a singular packet type. A packet definition contains a list of packets and is good for when numerous different packet types could arrive on a packet interface. Packet types in these definitions are separated by packet IDs, and the packet id must be referenced exactly in a previous static definition to decode a packet in a packet definition. For example, If packets &amp;quot;a&amp;quot;,&amp;quot;b&amp;quot;, and &amp;quot;c&amp;quot; could be recieved on a udp interface, a header definition defining a header must contain a field that can only be &amp;quot;a&amp;quot;,&amp;quot;b&amp;quot;, or &amp;quot;c&amp;quot;.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/body&gt;&lt;/html&gt;</string>
         </property>
         <property name="text">
          <string>Telemetry Definitions:</string>
         </property>
        </widget>
       </item>
